=You are a senior software engineer doing sprint planning.

Estimate the following GitHub issue using Fibonacci story points (1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13). Consider complexity, unknowns, and scope.

Issue #{{ $json.number }}: {{ $json.title }}

Labels: {{ $json.labels.map(l => l.name).join(', ') || 'none' }}

Body:
{{ $json.body || 'No description provided.' }}

Respond ONLY with a valid JSON object in this exact format (no markdown, no extra text):
{
  "number": {{ $json.number }},
  "title": "{{ $json.title.replace(/"/g, "'") }}",
  "labels": {{ JSON.stringify($json.labels.map(l => l.name)) }},
  "estimate": <fibonacci number>,
  "rationale": "<one sentence explanation>"
}

parameters.jsCode:
// Pull all outputs produced by the Estimate Issue agent across every loop iteration
const agentItems = $('Estimate Issue (Fibonacci)').all();

const estimates = [];

for (const item of agentItems) {
  const output = item.json.output || item.json.text || item.json.message || '';

  try {
    const cleaned = output.replace(/```json[\s\S]*?```/g, s => s.slice(s.indexOf('{'), s.lastIndexOf('}') + 1))
                          .replace(/```/g, '')
                          .trim();
    // Find the JSON object inside the string in case there is surrounding text
    const jsonStart = cleaned.indexOf('{');
    const jsonEnd   = cleaned.lastIndexOf('}');
    if (jsonStart === -1 || jsonEnd === -1) throw new Error('No JSON object found');
    const parsed = JSON.parse(cleaned.slice(jsonStart, jsonEnd + 1));
    estimates.push(parsed);
  } catch (e) {
    estimates.push({
      number: null,
      title: 'Unknown',
      labels: [],
      estimate: null,
      rationale: 'Could not parse estimate: ' + output.substring(0, 100)
    });
  }
}

return [{ json: { estimates } }];

parameters.text:
=You are a product manager organizing sprint priorities.

Below are raw sprint planning notes. Parse them and return a structured priority list.

Priority Notes:
{{ $json.priorityNotes }}

Respond ONLY with a valid JSON object in this exact format (no markdown, no extra text):
{
  "high": ["<issue topic or keyword>"],
  "medium": ["<issue topic or keyword>"],
  "low": ["<issue topic or keyword>"]
}

